introduction.p:
In this , we learned to write a system of linear equations as a matrix equation Ax=b.  This notation is suggestive: can we solve the system by dividing by A?  In other words, does the expression
 \text{\raisebox{1em}{``}}x = \frac bA\text{\raisebox{1em}{''}} 
make sense?  If so, then Ax=b would have exactly one solution for every value of b, namely, x=\text{\raisebox{1mm}{``}}\frac bA\text{\raisebox{1mm}{''}}.  According to this fact, this is the case if and only if the augmented matrix \mat{A b} has a pivot in every non-augmented column and no pivot in the augmented column, for every value of b.  That is, the row echelon form would have to look like this:

  \def\r{\color{seq-red}}
  \amat{
    \r\star, \star,   \star, b_1;
    0,     \r\star,   \star, b_2;
    0,           0, \r\star, b_3}
  \qquad
    {\r\star} = \text{pivot.}

Each non-augmented column must have a pivot, and there can be no row of zeros to the left of the augmentation line, since

  \def\r{\color{seq-red}}
  \amat{
    \r\star, \star,   \star, b_1;
    0,     \r\star,   \star, b_2;
    0,           0, \r\star, b_3;
    0,           0,       0, b_4;
  }

has no solution when b_4 = 0.  It follows that every row and every column of the coefficient matrix A needs to have a pivot, which can happen only when A is square.

bluebox.p:
If A is invertible then

  AB = AC \quad\implies\quad B = C \sptxt{and}
  BA = CA \quad\implies\quad B = C.

example.p:
On the other hand, the matrix

  \mat{1 0; 0 0}

from this  is in reduced row echelon form, and it is not the identity matrix, so it is not invertible by the second property.

solution.p:
          We augment by the identity and perform Gaussian elimination, which only requires one row operation in this case:

            \def\r{\color{seq-red}}
            \hmat{1 0 4 1 0 0; 0  1 2 0 1 0; 0 -3 -4 0 0 1}
            \quad\xrightarrow{R_3 \pluseq 3R_2}\quad
            \hmat{\r1 0 4 1 0 0; 0 \r1 2 0 1 0; 0 0 \r2 0 3 1}.

          All three pivots are to the left of the augmentation line, so A is invertible.  We continue with Jordan substitution:

            \begin{split}
              \hmat{1 0 4 1 0 0; 0 1 2 0 1 0; 0 0 2 0 3 1}
              \quad\xrightarrow{R_3\diveq 2}\quad
              &\hmat{1 0 4 1 0 0; 0 1 2 0 1 0; 0 0 1 0 3/2 1/2} \\
              \quad\xrightarrow[R_2\minuseq 2R_3]{R_1\minuseq 4R_3}\quad
              &\hmat{1 0 0 1 -6 -2; 0 1 0 0 -2 -1; 0 0 1 0 3/2 1/2}.
            \end{split}

          According to the , the inverse matrix is
          \mat{1 0 4; 0 1 2; 0 -3 -4}\inv = \mat{1 -6 -2; 0 -2 -1; 0 3/2 1/2}.
          We check:
          \mat{1 0 4; 0 1 2; 0 -3 -4}\mat{1 -6 -2; 0 -2 -1; 0 3/2 1/2}
= \ mat{1 0 0; 0 1 0; 0 0 1}. \qquad\bigcheck

We augment by the identity and perform Gaussian elimination:

  \def\r{\color{seq-red}}
  \hmat{1 0 4 1 0 0; 0  1 2 0 1 0; 0 -3 -6 0 0 1}
  \quad\xrightarrow{R_3\pluseq 3R_2}\quad
  \hmat{\r1 0 4 1 0 0; 0 \r1 2 0 1 0; 0 0 0 0 \r3 1}.

At this point we can stop, because one of the pivots is to the right of the augmentation line: the matrix A is not invertible.

statement.p:
Compute the inverse of the matrix
 A = \mat{2 3; 1 2} 
from this .

subsection.p:
Now we return to the question of solving Ax=b by dividing by A. Suppose that A is invertible. Then
\begin{split} Ax = b &\iff A\inv(Ax) = A\inv b \\ &\iff (A\inv A)x = A\inv b \\ &\iff I_nx = A\inv b \\ &\iff x = A\inv b. \end{split}
In other words, Ax=b has exactly one solution for every value of b, namely, b = A\inv x.

statement.p:
Solve the system

  \syseq{2x_1 + 3x_2 = b_1; x_1 + 2x_2 = b_2}

for x_1,x_2 in terms of b_1,b_2.

answer.p:
We can check our solution by substituting our expressions for x_1,x_2 into our original equations:

  \syseq{
    2x_1 + 3x_2 = 2(2b_1-3b_2) + 3(-b_1+2b_2) = (4-3)b_1 + (-6+6)b_2 = b_1;
    x_1 + 2x_2 = (2b_1-3b_2) + 2(-b_1+2b_2) = (2-2)b_1 + (-3+4)b_2 = b_2\rlap.
  }
